The family of former Liberian president Charles Taylor expressed concerns over the imbalance in legal representation, with the prosecution having more senior counsels than the defense.
They also criticized the installation of video surveillance in Taylor's meetings with his lawyers, hindering his ability to freely discuss his case.
Taylor's lawyers demanded more time to prepare for the trial, citing difficulties in securing witnesses due to travel bans.
The prosecutor assured a fair trial, emphasizing the need for adequate defense resources.
Taylor, facing war crimes charges, awaits trial in The Hague amid logistical and legal challenges.
